<h3><center>Abstract</center></h3>
A simulation of the Drossel-Schwabl model on a 200 x 200 lattice is performed. Eight values of $\theta=p/f$ and two initial conditions are shown to converge to the same state after 80 time steps. The state is shown to exhibit power-law correlations, proving its criticality. Values of critical exponents are calculated, only one of which is in agreement with the literature. A reason for this discrepancy is speculated. The average cluster size is shown to be time independent, agreeing with literature, and calculated. The results obtained can be generalized for $\theta \in [50,4000]$.

<h3><center>Introduction</center></h3>
Self-organized criticality (SOC) has been proposed by Bak, Chen and Tang as an explanation of a "1/f" noise present in a variety of systems [1]. Their paper is credited with introducing the concept of SOC via the sandpile model [2,3]. 

As the name suggests, it proposes a system that evolves to a critical point without fine-tunning, which is required for most systems that exhibit criticality. This is due to the fact such behaviour appears when a fixed point changes stability. The change in characteristic scales results in power-law correlations [4]. However, in an SOC system fine-tunning is not needed, as the critical point in an attractor [1]. This means that such systems naturally evolve to a critical state.

In a subsequent paper, Bak et al. attempted to apply their model to forest fires. This involved considering a small tree growth rate, p, and one fire source that propagates through the forest. The team has run simulations that exhibit the SOC behaviour desired, in the limit $p\rightarrow0$. [5]

Investigations on larger lattices and smaller p values revealed the formation of noisy spiral fire fronts. As p approaches 0 this spirals become less noisy. Both the characteristic length scale and time between two passings of a front scale as 1/p. [6,7] This shows that the behaviour doesn't become more critical as p approaches 0; on the contrary, becoming deterministic. The regular shape of the fire fronts poses a problem as well, since a critical system contains fronts of varied sizes, forming a power law frequency spectrum [8]. Since the behaviour is deterministic and the scaling determined by p, it is clear that the Bak-Chen-Tang model is not fit to describe forest fires. This is why it is currently referred to as a sandpile model [2].

Drossel and Schwabl modified the model by introducing the probability for a tree to catch fire independently, f. They showed the only relevant parameter to be the ratio $\theta=p/f$. SOC behaviour is shown for a double separation of time scales: $(f/p)^{-1/d}<<1/p<< 1/f$, where d is the dimension of the lattice. This means that the mean lifetime of a fire is much less than the average time to grow a tree, which, in turn, is much less than the time between two lightning strikes. In order to avoid finite size effects, the size of the largest cluster must be smaller than the number of sites used ($L^d$). This ensures that the mean cluster size will be independent of the lattice size. [8]

This report checks the scaling laws and critical exponents obtained for a two dimensional Drossel-Schwabl model, in the $(f/p)^{-1/d}<<1/p<< 1/f$ limit. This limit is equivalent with $f<<p<< \theta^{1/d}$ which is a more convenient form that is used later in this report.

<h3><center>Theory</center></h3>

Starting with the paper introducing the concept [1], cellular automata (CA) models have been useful in analysing SOC behaviour. These models approximate space and time to discrete units that can be in a finite number of discrete states. Usually, CA models follow a set of simple rules applied to all units[9]. In the case of the Drossel-Schwabl model this rules are[8]:
<ol start="1">
 <li>A tree burns in one time step, resulting in an empty plot</li>
 <li>A tree catches fire if at least one neighbour is on fire</li>
 <li>A tree grows with probability p, in one time step, on an empty plot</li>
 <li>A tree catches fire with probability f per time step, if it has no burning neighbours</li>
</ol>
, with rule number 4 being the one added by Drossel and Schwabl to the Bak-Chen-Tang model. These rules are run on a d-dimensional hypercubic lattice with L sites. In the case of this review a two-dimensional system is explored, meaning an L x L square lattice is used.

In order to test for SOC behaviour a more rigorous definition of it needs to be defined. As stated before, the point where criticality is observed needs to be an attractor, meaning that changing parameters and initial states does not change the final behaviour. In this report critical behaviour will be defined as one exhibiting critical spatiotemporal correlations, meaning that correlations follow a power-law, making them scale invariant. There are two other definitions of such behaviour: critical thresholds and critical global control parameters. [3] The first of the two refers to the threshold where the stable behaviour begins. This definition is looser then the one chosen, as it makes no attempts to describe the behaviour once started. The threshold will be found and labeled as "threshold value" as urged by Watkins et al. in [3]. In the second discarded definition, a global order parameter needs to reach a critical value for the system to be critical. In the sandpile model this parameter is the average slope of the piles. For the forest fire model this parameter will be assumed to be the average cluster size and calculated, since the size of the cluster represents its susceptability to being included in a fire, just as the slope of a sand pile controls its susceptibility to toppling. However, there is more literature available on the power-law definition, rather than the global order parameter, therefore, the first definition has been chosen.

Therefore, a system will be considered critical after exhibiting scale invariance, in the form of power-law correlations. Scale invariance is the property of a function to remain constant, in either shape or behaviour, when considered on a different scale, such that:
$$
\\
f(\lambda x)=g(\lambda)f(x)
\\
$$
,with f(x) being the invariant function, $\lambda $ modifies the scale and $g(\lambda)$ is independent of x.[10]

Power-laws do satisfy this relationship, if $f(x) = x^\alpha$:
$$
f(\lambda x)=(\lambda x)^\alpha=\lambda^\alpha x^\alpha=\lambda^\alpha f(x)
$$
, so $g(\lambda)=\lambda^\alpha$, independent of x.

In a system of independently random events f(x) is the probability distribution of the entire system which is obtained by multiplying all combinations of event probabilities between themselves. Let one combination of events have the probability:

$$
Prob_a=P_iP_j...P_k
$$
,with $Prob_a$ being the probability that events i,j,...k happened.  
Therefore x has to choose a state from distribution f(x) and let f(x) equal the probability of the chosen state. Meaning: 

$$
f(x)=\Sigma_{a=0}^{N}Prob_a \delta(x-\alpha_{a}),N >> 1
$$
,where $\alpha_{a}$ is a unique coefficient for each event combination.

Therefore:

$$
f(\lambda x) = \Sigma_{a=0}^{N}Prob_a \delta(\lambda x-\alpha_{a})
\\
\delta(\lambda x-\alpha_{a}) \neq \delta(x-\alpha_{a})=>
\Sigma_{a=0}^{N}Prob_a \delta(\lambda x-\alpha_{a})=Prob_b\neq Prob_a.
$$

Since the events are independent there is no reason to assume that $Prob_b = g(\lambda) Prob_a$, so:

$$
f(\lambda x) \neq g(\lambda)Prob_a.
$$

In conclusion, a system formed of randomly independent events is not expected to exhibit spacial invariance, but a power-law always has this feature.

<h3><center>Method</center></h3>

This report will run a Drossel and Schwabl model on a square lattice, using Python, following the rules:
<ol start="1">
 <li>A tree burns in one time step, resulting in an empty plot</li>
 <li>A tree catches fire if at least one neighbour is on fire</li>
 <li>A tree grows with probability $p=growth$, in one time step, on an empty plot</li>
 <li>A tree catches fire with probability $f=strike$ per time step, if it has no burning neighbours.</li>
</ol>

Each function defined will be followed by one or more tests in order to ensure proper functioning. After defining the function running the model, a short passage will comment on the default values and show they are in the desired limit. An animation is run in order to check the behaviour of the main function, some smaller scale tests are run as well. In order to find a rough estimate of the threshold value, the proportion of live trees with respect to time steps will be plotted. This will show the amount of time needed for the system to stabilize. Then the same plot is made for a variety of $\theta$ values and two initial forest densities, in order to check for the attractor property of the state. The threshold value will be read from the graph. In order to prove the stable state to be critical, two functions are defined to identify clusters of live trees and analyse them. Both are tested. The number, radius and circumference of clusters are plotted with respect to their area. All exhibit power-law correlations, which are also tested for $\theta = 4000$. The critical global control parameter is calculated. The results are summarised, then analysed and compared to the values in literature. 

The estimated time for loading of the entire notebook is three minutes.

The following function initialises the forest as an L x L numpy array. It starts by populating the array with random numbers between 0 and 1. A mask is made, where the values higher than the variable prop correspond to true. The true values are assigned empty plots and the rest are assigned trees.


```python
def forest(l,prop = 0.5):
    """
    Returns an l by l grid with randomly positioned trees, covering, approximately, the proportion specified
    l length of lattice 
    prop, optional, proportion of forest covered by trees, 0.5 by default
    """
    f = np.random.rand(l,l)
    mask = f > prop
    f[mask] = 0                    #empty plots are represented by 0
    f[np.logical_not(mask)] = 1    #plots with trees are represented by 1
    return f
```

The function below spreads a fire previously ignited. It takes the position of a burning tree and burns it. Then it sets on fire all its closest neighbours.


```python
def burn(f,p,l):
    """
    Spreads the fire in forest f from the plot of coordonates p
    Returns a list of new coordonates where new fires started
    f array-like representing the forest (must be a square matrix)
    p position of burning tree
    l length of forest
    """
    n = p[0]
    m = p[1]
    new = []                                              #list of positions of new burning trees
    f[n][m] = 0                                           #resets the burned tree to an empty plot
    for i in [-1,1]:
        if n+i!= -1 and n+i < l:                          #checks for the index to be in range
            if f[n+i][m] > 0:                             #checks for trees above and below
                f[n+i][m] = -1                            #sets fire to tree
                new.append([n+i,m])                       #adds new location
        if m+i != -1 and m+i < l:                         #checks for the index to be in range
            if f[n][m+i] > 0:                             #checks for trees left and right
                f[n][m+i] = -1                            #sets fire to tree
                new.append([n,m+i])                       #adds new location
    return new
```

The following function performs the rules of the Drossel-Schwabl model on a predefined lattice representing the forest.

Originally, the function used loops for finding trees and empty plots and attempted to light up, respectively plant a tree, for each position. Learning that np.nonzero(f== 1 or 0) returns the positions of trees and empty plots, respectively, has revealed a number of optimisations through the program. The method has been found on [stackoverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16094563/numpy-get-index-where-value-is-true) and verified through the [manual](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.nonzero.html). The function np.nonzero(condition) finds the indices of all locations where the condition is true, in the form $[y_0,y_1,..][x_0,x_1,..],...$ for a 2D array. This function is used extensively throughout the program. The condition np.random.random() < strike (or growth), used originally, was replaced with np.random.random(len(position_array)) < strike (or growth). This made the loop run over the trees set of fire and the plots growing trees, rather than all plots in the lattice.


```python
def forest_fire(f,l,t_fin,strike = 0.001,growth = 0.1):
    """
    Modifies the forest f by burning a random tree with probability strike and growing a tree on an empty plot 
    with probability growth for every time step between 0 and t_fin.
    Returns an array, F, were each element is the state of forest f at time i, where i is the index of F where f is found
    f array-like representing the forest (must be a square matrix)
    l length of forest
    t_fin amount of time the model will run for
    strike, optional, probability of spontaneously setting a tree on fire in one time step, 0.001 by default
    growth, optional, probability of growing a tree in one time step, 0.1 by default
    """
    F = []                                              #list containing the states of forests
    i = 0
    b = []                                              #list of burning trees
    for t in np.arange(1,t_fin+1):
        trees = np.array(np.nonzero(f==1))              #find indeces of all trees in form [y0,y1,..][x0,x1,..]
        mask = np.random.random(len(trees.T)) < strike  #mask for all trees that cought fire this time step
        if mask.any():                                  #chacks if any tree has been set on fire
            nt = trees[0][mask]                         #line numbers of all trees to be burned
            mt = trees[1][mask]                         #column numbers of all trees to be burned
            for j in np.arange(len(nt)):                #go through all trees to be burned
                n = nt[j]
                m = mt[j]
                b.append([n,m])                         #save the position as burning
                f[n][m] = -1                            #light up the tree
        plot = np.array(np.nonzero(f==0))               #find indeces of all trees in form [x0,x1,..][y0,y1,..]
        mask = np.random.random(len(plot.T)) < growth   #mask for all plots that grew a tree this time step
        if mask.any():                                  #chacks if any tree grew
            nt = plot[0][mask]                          #line numbers of all growing trees
            mt = plot[1][mask]                          #column numbers of all growing trees
            for j in np.arange(len(nt)):                #go through all plots that will grow trees
                n = nt[j]
                m = mt[j]
                f[n][m] = 1                             #grow a new tree
        N = len(b)          #ensures that the fire will spread only at the nearest neighbours of currently burning trees
        while i < N:
            p = burn(f,b[i],l)                          #burn current plot and find the adjecent trees to be burned
            for a in p:
                b.append(a)                             #save the coordinates of the trees adjecent to a burning tree
            i += 1
        f_copy = f.copy()
        F.append(f_copy)                                #save a copy, as the original is continuosly modified
    return np.array(F)
```

As stated before, strike and growth are the equivalent of f and p respectively. Meaning, $strike << growth << \theta^{1/2} $. The defined default values (strike = 0.001, growth = 0.1) result in $\theta = 100 => \theta^{1/2} =10$, therefore $0.001<<0.1<<10$, placing this values in the desired limit.

In order to define an acceptable range of $\theta$, the growth parameter will be fixed at 0.1, meaning: $$\frac{0.1}{\theta} << 0.1 << \sqrt \theta.$$

This relationship makes it clear that any $\theta > 10$ is acceptable. However, it is important to keep in mind that a  larger $\theta$ leads to a lower probability of spontaneous fires, allowing for larger clusters. Therefore, values of $\theta$ that are too high will exhibit finite size effects.

The animations roughly follow the same behaviour. Before the first fires reach the edge of the lattice the forest becomes much denser, after the first fires spread in the whole lattice the density is much lower. This repeats a number of times until a steady state is achieved.

In order to investigate this behaviour more rigorously and find the threshold value the proportion to which the lattice is occupied with trees is used. First, a graph with the default value of $\theta = 100$ is made in order to see the range where it is expected. The graph is plotted for the two lattice sizes previously used (50 x 50 and 200 x 200). A subplot of the last half of the data points is graphed in order to see the change in occupancy in the stable state. The highest change in occupancy (the difference between the highest and the lowest occupancy) for this state is calculated.

Optimisation has been done by using np.sum() to calculate the proportion of forest occupied. The code takes about 20 seconds to run.



It is clear that the two simulations are very similar at the start, but the larger lattice evolves into a more stable system. Due to this fact, the following analysis will be performed on the 200 x 200 lattice.

The stable state is clearly set in from 100 time steps, therefore, the following plot, with multiple $\theta$ values, runs for 100 time steps. Two initial forests are used, an empty one and a half occupied one, represented by red and blue respectively.

The code below runs in under a minute.


```python
#define ploting space
fig, (ax1,ax2,ax3) = plt.subplots(3,1,figsize = [8,16])

#set parameters
t_fin = 100
l_grid = 200
theta_list = [10, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000, 2000, 4000]     #theta values used for the analysis
#initialise variables
f5 = forest(l_grid, prop = 0.5)                            #set up a forest, populated in a proportion of 50%
f0 = forest(l_grid, prop = 0)                              #set up an empty forest
T = np.arange(1,t_fin + 1)                                 #array of time steps
change = [[],[]]                                           #list of ocillation amplitudes after stable state
#set up colour maps
N = len(theta_list)
colors5 = plt.cm.Blues(np.linspace(0,1,N+3))               #colour map for the lattice starting up 50% occupied
colors0 = plt.cm.Reds(np.linspace(0,1,N+3))                #colour map for the lattice starting up empty
i = 2

for theta in theta_list:                                   #for each theta value in theta_list
    strike = 0.1/theta
    f_copy = f5.copy()                                     #work on a copy of the forest
    F = forest_fire(f_copy,l_grid,t_fin,strike = strike)   #array of forest states
    prop = np.sum(F == 1,axis = (1,2))/l_grid**2           #calculate proportion of trees in lattice
    ax1.plot(T,prop,c = colors5[i],label = '$\\theta =$'+str(theta))
    slice_t = 80                                           #stable state is assumed to start at 80 time steps
    crit_prop = prop[slice_t:]                             #zooming in the portion after the expected threshold value
    ax2.plot(T[slice_t:],crit_prop,c = colors5[i],label = '$\\theta =$'+str(theta))  
    change[0].append(round((np.max(crit_prop)-np.min(crit_prop))*100,3)) #calculate and store the change in occupancy
    f_copy = f0.copy()
    F = forest_fire(f_copy,l_grid,t_fin,strike = strike)   #array of forest states
    prop = np.sum(F == 1,axis = (1,2))/l_grid**2           #calculate proportion of trees in lattice
    ax1.plot(T,prop,c = colors0[i],label = '$\\theta =$'+str(theta))
    slice_t = 80                                           #stable state is assumed to start at 80 time steps
    crit_prop = prop[slice_t:]                             #zooming in the portion after the expected threshold value
    ax2.plot(T[slice_t:],crit_prop,c = colors0[i],label = '$\\theta =$'+str(theta))  
    change[1].append(round((np.max(crit_prop)-np.min(crit_prop))*100,3)) #calculate and store the change in occupancy
```

In order to analyse the correlation between properties of clusters they first need to be identified. The function below identifies clusters using the Hoshen–Kopelman algorithm and assigned them an index number.


```python
def find_clusters(f,l_grid):
    """
    Counts clusters of live trees in forest f by looking for neigbours above and to the left of each tree.
    The Hoshen–Kopelman algorithm is used: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hoshen%E2%80%93Kopelman_algorithm.
    Returns an array of the same shape as the forest array with each cluster being assigned an integer, 
    the integers aren't necessarily consecutive. 
    f array-like representing the forest (must be of shape l x l)
    l_grid length of array
    """
    above = 0
    left = 0
    clusters = np.zeros((l_grid,l_grid),dtype = np.uint16)  
    #only integer positive values are needed, so the uint16 type is sufficient
    index = 1
    trees = np.array(np.nonzero(f==1))
    for j in np.arange(len(trees.T)):
        n = trees[0][j]
        m = trees[1][j]
        #find the index of the clusters above and to the left, if none keep as 0
        above = 0
        left = 0
        if n-1 != -1 and f[n-1][m] == 1:
            above = clusters[n-1][m]           #index of the cluster above, if existant
        if m-1 != -1 and f[n][m-1] == 1:
            left = clusters[n][m-1]            #index of the cluster to the left, if existant
        #assign index to tree in the following cases
        if left == 0 and above == 0:           #no adjecent clusters
            clusters[n][m] = index
            index += 1                         #create new cluster
        elif left == 0 or above == 0:          #one adjecent cluster
            clusters[n][m] = left + above      #assingn index of adjecent cluster, no need to create a new one
        else:                                  #two adjecent clusters, they need to be unified
            if above > left:                   #find lower index
                index0 = above                 #store higher index as index0(will be eliminated)
                index1 = left                  #store lower index as index1 (will be kept)
            else:
                index0 = left
                index1 = above
            clusters[n][m] = index1           #assingn current tree the lower index
            for p in np.transpose((clusters == index0).nonzero()):  
                clusters[p[0]][p[1]] = index1 
                #all trees of the higher index are now merged into the cluster with the lower index
                #because of this merging of clusters not all cluster idices will be consecutive
    return clusters
```

The following function can calculate the area, circumference and radius of clusters given in the output format of the find_clusters() function. Area is defined as the number of trees in the cluster. Circumference is defined as the number of sides connecting a plot with a tree to one without. Radius is defined as the mean distance of the cluster members from the cluster center, which is taken to be the mean position of all trees in the cluster. The position of the centers of clusters is also returned for easier testing.
 
To optimise the function the area calculation was taken out of the loop over cluster idices and, more importantly, the function np.unique() is used. This function returns the unique values of an array along with an optional array counting the number of instances. There are other optional outputs unused.


```python
def analyse_clusters(C, l, calc_area = True, calc_circ = True, calc_r = True):
    """
    Finds the area, circumference and/or radius of each cluster. 
    Returns 5 lists containing the following information about each cluster: area, circumference, radius, x component 
    of center, y component of center. One or more lists might be empty if the corresponding bool is set to False.
    f array-like representing the forest (must be of shape n x n)
    l length and width of array
    calc_area, opt,bool, decides if the area will be calculated
    calc_circ, opt,bool, decides if the circumference will be calculated
    calc_r, opt,bool, decides if the radius will be calculated (radius is defined as the mean 
    distance of the cluster members from the center)
    """
    area = []
    xm = []
    ym = []
    r = []
    circ = []
    val, a = np.unique(C, return_counts=True)
    if calc_area:
        area = a[1:]                           #exculdes empty plots
    if calc_circ or calc_r:
        val = val[1:]                          #exculdes empty plots
        for i in val:
            p = np.array(np.nonzero(C==i))     #gets possitions of all trees in the cluster
            if calc_circ:
                c = 0
                for n,m in p.T:                    #for all trees in the cluster
                    for k in [-1,1]:
                        if n+k < l and n+k > -1:   #if in range
                            if C[n+k][m] == 0:     #and has a empty plot as neighbour
                                c += 1             #add one to circumference
                        else:
                            c += 1                 #if the cluster is at the edge of the lattice, count it as well 
                        if m+k < l and m+k > -1:   #if in range
                            if C[n][m+k] == 0:     #and has a empty plot as neighbour
                                c += 1             #add one to circumference
                        else:
                            c += 1                 #if the cluster is at the edge of the lattice, count it as well 
                circ.append(c)
            if calc_r:
                y = p[0]
                x = p[1]
                xm.append(np.mean(x))                                #x coordonate of center
                ym.append(np.mean(y))                                #y coordonate of center
                ri = np.sqrt((x-np.mean(x))**2 + (y-np.mean(y))**2)  #calculate the distance between the center and all trees
                r.append(np.mean(ri))                                #take the mean of the distances
    return area,circ,r,xm,ym
```

The analysis will be made on a lattice of length 200 with the value $\theta = 100$. The power-laws will be checked for $\theta = 4000$ as well.

The following code takes about 40 sec to load. The code has been optimised by using the list.extend() method. Another optimisation was done in the radius and circumference calculation. For every area value a mask is used to set all but the values describing the desired area, to zero. This ensures that summing over the array will be dependent only on the relevant values. The average is taken by summing the masked array and dividing it by the number of clusters with that area. 


```python
def power_law(x,m,b):
    return (x**m)*b
```


```python
#set parameters
t_fin = 100
l_grid = 200
threshold_value = 80
#initialise variables
area = []
radius = []
circ = []
R = []
circumference = []
#initialise forest
f = forest(l_grid)                                    #original forest
F = forest_fire(f,l_grid,t_fin)                       #array of forest states
print('Finished iterations. Retrieving data.')
for f in F[threshold_value:]:                         #selects the interval with stable behaviour
    C = find_clusters(f,l_grid)                       #get map with numbered clusters
    a,c,r = analyse_clusters(C,l_grid)[:-2]           #get lists of characteristics of clusters
    area.extend(a)
    circ.extend(c)
    radius.extend(r)   
print('Finished retrieving data. Sort data.')
s, N = np.unique(area,return_counts = True)          #get arrays of area and frequency
circ = np.array(circ)                                #transfor to array for broadcasting
radius = np.array(radius)                            #transfor to array for broadcasting
for i in np.arange(len(s)):                          #loop over all area values
    mask = (area != s[i])                            #create mask to select relevant data
    tmp_r = radius.copy()
    tmp_c = circ.copy()
    tmp_r[mask] = 0                                  #set non relevant values to 0
    tmp_c[mask] = 0                                  #set non relevant values to 0
    R.append(np.sum(tmp_r)/N[i])                     #append average
    circumference.append(np.sum(tmp_c)/N[i])          #append average
#plot
fig, (ax1,ax2,ax3) = plt.subplots(3,1,figsize=[8,15])
ax1.scatter(s,N,label= 'data')
popt, pcov = optimize.curve_fit(power_law,s,N)                     #fit power law to graph
fit = [popt[0], np.sqrt(pcov[0][0]), popt[1], np.sqrt(pcov[1][1])]
ax1.plot(s,power_law(s,*popt), color='red',label='fit: $b \ s^{m}$ with m=%5.3f$\pm$%5.3f, b=%5.0f$\pm$%5.0f' % tuple(fit))

ax2.plot(s,power_law(s,*popt), color='red',label='fit: $b \ s^{m}$ with m=%5.3f$\pm$%5.3f, b=%5.3f$\pm$%5.3f' % tuple(fit))
ax2.set_title('Log-log plot of the radius of clusters with respect to its area')

ax2.set_ylabel('Radius of cluster')
ax3.scatter(s,circumference,label= 'data')

ax3.plot(s,power_law(s,*popt), color='red',label='fit: $b \ s^{m}$ with m=%5.3f$\pm$%5.3f, b=%5.3f$\pm$%5.3f' % tuple(fit))
```

<h3><center>Results</center></h3>

The power-laws:
$$
N(s) \propto s^{-2} (1)\\
R(s) \propto s^{r}  (2)\\
C(s) \propto s^{c}  (3)
$$
have been found to characterise the behaviour of the model after the threshold value of 80 time steps. In the same regime, the value of the global order parameter has been found to be approximately 4.4 units.

<h3><center>Analysis and Discussion</center></h3>

Equation (1) agrees with the value obtained by Drossel and Schwabl, when introducing their model. [8] However, equation (2) poses more problems, as
$$
R(s) \propto s^{1/D}
$$
, where D is the fractal dimension of fires[8,11].

According to equation (2)
$$
r = \frac{1}{D} \in [0.53,0.63] => \\
D \in [1.58,1.88].
$$
However, $D \in [1.96,2]$[12,13]. This error might be due to the size of the lattice used in this report being much smaller than the ones used in literature.

The average cluster size was found to be approximatively constant in the critical state. This is in line with the literature, as it is only dependent on $\theta$ and the mean forest density[8].

It is important to note that it is possible that the critical behaviour observed in the Drossel-Schwabl model, might not hold as $\theta \rightarrow \infty$[11]. Grassberger's analysis used large lattices ( up to 65 536 x 65 536) and large $\theta$ values (up to 256 000) to test the behaviour, finding few power-laws. Such values are beyond the scope of this report, but it is important to note such limitations. 

<h3><center>Summary and Conclusions</center></h3>

In this report the background of the Drossel-Schwabl model has been noted. The method, rules and time separation needed have been acknowledged and briefly explained. Criticality and scale invariance have been defined. It has been proven that scale invariance doesn't manifest in systems comprised of randomly independent events, while being present in power-law correlations. 

The methods used to run and test this model has been detailed. The quantities calculated in the report have been specified. All functions used in the report have been thoroughly tested. Once the function running the model has been written, a short passage ensured the parameters to be in the limits of the Drossel-Schwabl model. Two animations have been run in order to ensure the function behaves as expected. 

The proportion of trees in the lattice has been calculated in order to identify a threshold value. This value marks the system entering into a stable state, defined by minimal change in the degree of occupancy of the forest at any given time. The attractor property of stable state in SOC systems has been shown by varying $\theta = p/f$ and the initial state of the forest. By doing so, the threshold value was found to be 80 time steps.

Clusters of live trees have been identified and analysed. From the analysis three power-laws have been identified
$$
N(s) \propto s^{-2} \\
R(s) \propto s^{r} for \mspace{4mu} r\in \lbrace 0.53,0.63 \rbrace  \\
C(s) \propto s^{c} for \mspace{4mu} c\in \lbrace 0.94,0.97 \rbrace.
$$

The first agrees with the values in the literature, while the second implies a significantly smaller fractal dimension of fires. This effect is speculated to be caused by the much smaller lattice size of this report, compared to those used in literature. The average cluster size in the critical state was found to be independent of time, in 
accordance with other investigations.

It has been noted that at significantly higher $\theta$, only feasible with large lattices, the power-law dependence is not present. While technical limitations mean the present report can't verify this, it introduces caution in its generalizations.

In conclusion, for square lattices of size 200 x 200 and $\theta \in [50,4000]$, the Drossel-Schwabl model exhibits self-organised criticality. The critical state is an attractor in the aforementioned conditions, ensuring that no fine-tunning is required. The critical behaviour exhibits power-laws between the area of clusters and their number, radius and circumference and a time-independent cluster area average.
